'''Level 722''' is the 723<sup>rd</sup> level of the Backrooms.



<span id="header" style="font-size:36px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''''Level Description'''''</center></span>
{{Underline|ff4900}}
{{Blurimage|caption=The only photo captured of '''Level 722''', outside of the mineshaft.|file=722buttrue.png}}


Level 722 resembles the inside of a large mineshaft. The color scheme of the mineshaft will usually change whenever the temperature increases/decreases rapidly. In other words, the main "tint" of objects in the level will change to fit the temperature, i.e. a red tint for hot temperatures and a cyan tint for cold temperatures. Some explorers have noted that when the temperatures get blazing hot; there are no "heat waves". Rather the objects in the level appear on fire even if they are not. The level tends to have a faint yet almost burnt smell of [[Object 1|Almond Water]]. Explorers that have taken a whiff of this scent have ended up with psychological issues down the road, yet it is not confirmed whether this scent can psychologically damage a person.

The inside of the mineshaft will usually drop at most '''6x''' below absolute zero freezing anything immediately. Or in an opposite scenario; the temperature can spike all the way up to an estimated 80000° Celsius. While the temperature can drop below absolute zero, there are no confirmations of "negative atom movement" resulting from the freezing temperatures. Instead, the atoms will act as they usually do ''at'' absolute zero, but not below it.

The temperature does not change when standing outside of the mineshaft, nor does the temperature inside of the mineshaft carry over outside. Explorers have compared going back into the mineshaft when the temperatures are extremely hot to something like when a person opens an oven and stares right into it without letting it air out.

Because of specialized suits created by [[M.E.G.]], explorers are able to investigate the level when the temperature drops. The only downside is that the suits do not protect from the extreme heat. This would lead to explorers that have went too far into the level to not be able to make it out before the heat melts them and the suit. Alongside this, piles of melted metal have been found. They have been proven to be connected to the suits, yet any trace of a person who was said to be inhabiting said suit was not found. There have been speculations that an entity kidnaps an explorer from their suit, but this is highly unlikely as the suits are airtight and can only be opened from the inside.

The level also has many crevices scattered about that have yet to be explored to their fullest due to the anomalous properties that a crevice may possess. The dangers of this level and its areas have not been completely documented. Exploration of this level is ill-advised unless traveling with a guaranteed way of making it out when the temperature rapidly and unpredictably undergoes change. 

Because of the extreme temperatures of this level, no explorer has photographed the inside of the mineshaft due to camera malfunctions. [[M.E.G]] is still in development of a camera that is resistant to these temperatures, but there have been no results thus far.

Explorers have also reported severe cases of psychological damage the further they explore down the mineshaft. Some people have even developed previously thought-to-be hereditary mental illnesses such as '''Autism''', '''ADHD''', or in extremely rare cases, '''Schizophrenia'''. They also developed more common illnesses such as '''Paranoia''' and '''Depression''' (albeit it is unlikely).

In all cases of exploration for this level, certain areas are deemed extremely dangerous, while other areas are considered temporarily safe. However, the exception is that these "safe places" do not remain safe and stable; after some time, they are often found to have caved in. This poses a threat to anyone attempting to establish a colony in these areas. There is no confirmation that any location in this level is permanently safe including the outside of the mineshaft.

Crevices found across the level may pose a safe place from psychological and heat hazards, but they may also pose a threat depending on the stability of the crevice. It is best not to trust any crevices safety as many crevices that have been discovered were found caved in a week later following the levels periodic decay. Despite numerous speculations, it is still unknown if the decay is sentient.

Every square foot of the level is to be deemed dangerous by unknowing explorers. Any explorers that want to document this level are encouraged to proceed in an alert fashion and with utmost caution. Explorers are also encouraged to document anomalies and abnormalities if they are to encounter them.

Occasional puddles are found throughout the level. According to studies, these puddles are immune to the extreme temperatures and do not freeze nor do they evaporate when the temperature rapidly changes. Explorers have collected samples of the puddle and scientists are studying its composition. Scientists have confirmed that the liquid is '''''not''''' water and that there is no confirmation the puddles are sentient beings or an anomalous element. 

Explorers have also confirmed the puddles are extremely deep and are always at room temperature (21° Celsius). There is, however, no confirmation that these puddles pose as a safezone from the extreme temperatures as some explorers have speculated. 

The puddles do pose a drowning risk due to their depth with the deepest puddle recorded being nearly 1900 meters deep. No more efforts have been taken to measure the size of other puddles as they are further down into the level and may pose a risk for explorers and journalists alike.

The wood used in the mineshaft is also not composed of any element found in the periodic table. Despite this, the wood behaves like normal wood and can be set on fire manually. The levels rapid temperature changes do not alter it except only make it extremely hot or cold to the touch. Explorers have carved symbols into the wood to represent how far explorations have gone. The symbols ''may'' resemble any of these below:  {{Blurimage|caption=This symbol represents a successful exploration of the current area.|file=Symbol2.png}}
{{Blurimage|caption=This symbol represents M.E.G.|file=Symbol1.png}}

These symbols alongside many others help communicate to unsuspecting explorers that may enter this level by pure accident. There are symbols that indicate danger among the areas as well.

Keep in mind that the symbols shown are not an accurate representation of their appearance and may differ between explorers or areas due to a number of factors such as but not limited to: desperation, material used to carve, handwriting, wood-size, strength, etc.













<span id="header" style="font-size:36px; color: #91fff7"><center>'''''Environmental Hazards'''''</center></span>
{{Underline|91fff7}}

Level 722s hazards have not been fully documented. Most explorers have only documented the rapid temperature changes and the periodic decay of the levels infrastructure.


<span style="font-size:24px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''''Temperature Hazards'''''</center></span>

Level 722s temperature has a habit of rapidly increasing and decreasing to extreme values unpredictably. Despite numerous attempts at finding a pattern or a way to infer when a temperature change could happen, all attempts have concluded no results. However, the temperature can vary from a specified range that [[M.E.G.]] officials have placed on it. As well as the fact that the temperatures are not always at an extreme and may reach 23-38° Celsius periodically, albeit this has only been recorded 7 times to have ever happened with the last time being an ''undetermined amount of time'' ago.

<span style="font-size:18px; color: #91fff7"><center>'''Lowest Temperature'''</center></span>

'''-1232° Celsius.''' This temperature was recorded after an explorer mentioned to other explorers that the temperature felt lower than usual. This ended up being the lowest anyone has caught the temperature to be. There is, however, speculation that it gets colder further in the level, yet that has not been confirmed. Keep in mind that the "Cold-Hearted" crevice is not taken into account.

<span style="font-size:18px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''Highest Temperature'''</center></span>

'''Around 81,000° Celsius.''' This temperature was the highest possible documented temperature as any other thermometer would implode. The thermometer that documented this temperature short-circuited within 3 seconds of documentation and hasn't been able to work since. There are theories that the temperature is much higher, but this has not been confirmed. Explorers were not actively inside of the mineshaft when documenting due to a multitude of safety procedures.



<span style="font-size:24px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''''Decay'''''</center></span>

Level 722 has a habit of its infrastructure decaying periodically. Explorers have theorized that the temperature causes decay to the materials, but this was disproved. Level 722s decay can vary from certain objects in the level, to large cave-ins. The decay may be noticeable at times and unnoticeable at other times. The decay will usually be noticeable when it correlates to a cave-in due to the screeching noise of rocks before the decay causes the aforementioned cave-in. Unlike the temperature, decays can be accurately predicted. Following a decay, there is an average time of '''16 minutes''' before the next decay happens. The furthest outlier from this number was only '''18 minutes'''. Explorers have reported cave-ins are caused by decay. There is uncertainty whether this level might become inaccessible in the future due to consistent cave-ins from the decay. The decay of the mineshaft is always tinted with cyan, no matter the current temperature of the level. There have been theories about an entity but observations and experiments have disproved this.


<span id="header" style="font-size:36px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''''Entities'''''</center></span>
{{Underline|ff4900}}

Despite numerous explorations, theories, and experimentation, there have been no discoveries of an entity in this level nor has any common entity forcefully placed in this level survived the temperatures. Speculations have risen that an "all-powerful" entity is altering the temperature however this has not been confirmed and is likely false. Speculations have also risen that an entity may be causing the decay, yet this was disproved on numerous counts. The most common speculation is that an entity carved out the mineshaft and abandoned it, yet this has also not been confirmed. There is, however, evidence to support it. The theorized entity is also speculated to not be human due to the abnormal width and length of the mineshaft.



<span id="header" style="font-size:36px; color: #91fff7"><center>'''''Unique Areas'''''</center></span>
{{Underline|91fff7}}

Level 722s mineshaft is greatly filled with many crevices large enough for average-sized explorers to enter, however, some explorers that have gone to explore certain crevices ''did not return.''


<span style="font-size:20px; color: #91fff7"><center>'''''Cold-Hearted''''' (Crevice)</center></span>

This is the first crevice an explorer may stumble upon. Its entrance resembles a heart and has a moderate size that decreases as one keeps exploring. The crevice is speculated to be man-made and not by chance, however studies have not confirmed this. Explorers have all gone to explore the crevice and it is treated as a safezone to explorers wearing [[M.E.G.]]s specialized suits during a rapid temperature spike, the crevices temperature is around -1249° Celsius and is the coldest temperature in the entire mineshaft so far and the temperature does not change. It is about '''6x''' as cold as absolute zero, however, the specialized suits make exploring this crevice feasible. The furthest any explorer has gotten through this crevice was 1.3 kilometers (0.8 miles) before the crevice was simply too small to fit through. Despite many explorers urging smaller-size explorers to enter the crevice and explore it more, all have refused due to the risk of any one of those explorers not returning. This is the most documented and well-known crevice within Level 722, it is also the only one that gradually decreases in size correlating to distance and the only one with an entrance nearly the height of 8 average-sized men and the width of 2 pick-up trucks length-wise. Explorers have attempted to stick long items through the smallest part of the crevice to see how far it goes and the longest item inserted was nearly 950 feet in length but no wall was hit, it is speculated the crevice continues forever yet this is not confirmed and is highly unlikely due to the decrease in size over time.


<span style="font-size:20px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''''This Heat, An Evil Heat''''' (Crevice)</center></span>

This is the second crevice an explorer may stumble upon. The entrance is about the size of an SUV. Observations have confirmed that this crevice is natural and not man-made, most likely caused from the decay. The inside of the crevice is at a constant of 150,000° Celsius. The hottest temperature in the mineshaft documented so far. No explorer has entered the crevice and anything thrown into it melts immediately and then evaporates, effectively getting vaporized in the span of half a second. The crevice goes as far as the eye can see but no one knows how far it truly goes, there is little known about this crevice and its unusual heat but many have speculated there's ALSO an entity heating up this crevice on the outside, this was disproved on 4 different counts. Explorers have stated that going near the crevice implants a feeling of dread and that they feel urged to enter, however, there is no documentation of an explorer falling victim to the urge ''as we know of.'' As cliche as the feeling is described, many explorers suffer permanent mental damage after too much exposure to the crevice. It is ill-advised to go near this crevice unless one is documenting the crevice and following proper safety procedures.


<span style="font-size:20px; color: #91fff7"><center>'''''The Bahr Trench''''' (Puddle)</center></span>

This is the only puddle with proper documentation and the deepest according to explorers. The puddle reaches a staggering 1900 meters deep and is the width of about an average human male. The puddles are not made out of any [[The Frontrooms| Frontrooms]] liquid substance or any Backrooms liquid substance (such as [[Object 1|Almond Water]]). The puddle consists of strange properties in which it does not freeze or boil when met with extreme temperatures. Observations from explorers have stated that the puddle appears to be always at room temperature (21° Celsius) and essentially just what is considered a "warm bath" by normal people. Explorers that have entered the puddle to investigate and document their findings have discovered new substances that [[M.E.G.]] scientists did not correlate to any existing element in the periodic table. The substances value is unknown and scientists have also determined that they are extremely radioactive, yet it is unknown the effect they may have on the water. No explorers have received any physical or psychological damage after exploring the puddle but they are discouraged to do it again.


<span style="font-size:20px; color: gray"><center>'''''Further Down The Mineshaft'''''</center></span>

Nothing has been documented further down. No explorer knows what to expect and simply does not want to investigate due to the extreme oscillating temperatures that could prevent the explorer from returning. There have been no attempts to go further, however, [[M.E.G.]] scientists are still attempting to make suits that protect from both the extreme hot and extreme cold alike. This region remains undocumented for now.


Any other locations that are not stated here were either irrelevant or simply too little known about them and too much disinterest after exploring them and proving they do not make further progressions in the level.


<span id="header" style="font-size:36px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''''Outposts, Bases, or Colonies'''''</center></span>
{{Underline|ff4900}}

No outposts, bases, or colonies have been created. The extreme temperatures of this level make it near impossible to build anything that can last and the safety of puddles is undetermined due to the radioactive substances. There was an attempt to make a colony outside of the mineshaft so they may collect and use the extreme temperatures for power, yet the colony failed as no technology could withstand the temperatures. A colony hasn't had an attempt at creation ''since.''


<span id="header" style="font-size:36px; color: #ff4900"><center>'''''Entrances and Exits'''''</center></span>
{{Underline|ff4900}}


<span style="font-size:24px; color: #91fff7"><center>'''''Entrances'''''</center></span>
* Entering through a small red-tinted crevice in [[Level 221]].
* Climbing a telephone pole on [[Level 9.7]] sends one here.
* Setting yourself on fire or freezing yourself in [[Level 8]]. (Found unintentionally, does cause physical damage even after noclipping into the level.)
* Running into a red tinted rock wall in any cave level at full speed has a minimal chance of bringing you here. You are discouraged to attempt this.
*Finding an abundance of coal on [[Level 132]] will take one here.

<span style="font-size:24px; color: #91fff7"><center>'''''Exits'''''</center></span>
* Jumping through a small hole outside of the mineshaft that leads to [[Level 8]].
* Drinking any water from the puddles lead you to [[Level 7]]. However it has been shown to cause bodily harm and you are discouraged to attempt this.



